      "type": "html",
      "text": "As heralded by Nygaard at the IFIP-62 World Congress and further evidenced by the SIMULA manual of May 1965, SIMULA I was a special-purpose language geared toward operations research problems. The 1960s saw an enormous proliferation of these so-called special-purpose languages.  This can be understood partly as a function of the changing perceptions about the computer itself as I argued earlier [...].  Since the computer increasingly came to be seen as general- purpose device, special-purpose software took over the function of configuring it for specialized application areas like simulation, for example.",
      "id": "16cf052b54bd66d90111790bb46352cd"
